eved from \"\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nuclear_weapon&oldid=1337841487\n\"\nCategories\n:\nNuclear weapons\nAmerican inventions\nBombs\nNuclear bombs\nWeapons and ammunition introduced in 1945\nHidden categories:\nAll articles with dead external links\nArticles with dead external links from March 2025\nWebarchive template wayback links\nAll accuracy disputes\nArticles with disputed statements from July 2013\nCS1 maint: archived copy as title\nArticles with short description\nShort description is different from Wikidata\nWikipedia pages semi-protected against vandalism\nWikipedia indefinitely move-protected pages\nArticles needing additional references from May 2022\nAll articles needing additional references\nUse mdy dates from February 2021\nPages using multiple image with auto scaled images\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2025\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from January 2016\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from May 2022\nArticles with unsourced statements from June 2013\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2012\nArticles with excerpts\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from March 2009\nCS1 errors: ISBN date\nArticles with French-language sources (fr)\nCommons link from Wikidata\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNuclear weapon\n133 languages\nAdd topic","chroma:document":"Prime Minister of Israel\nRequires agreement of the\nMinister of Defense\nand\nChief of the General Staff\n.\n[\n69\n]\nControversy\nSee also:\nNuclear weapons debate\nand\nHistory of the anti-nuclear movement\nEthics\nMain article:\nNuclear ethics\nAnti-nuclear weapons\nprotest march in Oxford, 1980\nEven before the first nuclear weapons had been developed, scientists involved with the\nManhattan Project\nwere divided over the use of the weapon. The role of the two atomic bombings of the country in\nJapan's surrender\nand the US's\nethical\njustification for them has been the subject of scholarly and popular debate for decades. The question of whether nations should have nuclear weapons, or test them, has been continually and nearly universally controversial.\n[\n75\n]\nNotable nuclear weapons accidents\nMain articles:\nNuclear and radiation accidents and incidents\nand\nList of military nuclear accidents\nSee also:\nList of nuclear close calls","source":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon","headers":"H2: ContentsH1: Nuclear weaponH2: Testing and deploymentH2: TypesH3: Fission weaponsH3: Fusion weaponsH3: Other typesH4: Tactical nuclear weaponsH2: Weapons deliveryH2: Nuclear strategyH2: Governance, control, and lawH3: DisarmamentH3: United NationsH2: Launch authorityH2: ControversyH3: EthicsH3: Notable nuclear weapons accidentsH3: Nuclear testing and falloutH2: Effects of nuclear explosionsH3: Effects of nuclear explosions on human healthH3: Effects of nuclear warH3: Public oppositionH2: Costs and technology spin-offsH2: Non-weapons usesH2: History of developmentH2: See alsoH2: NotesH2: ReferencesH3: BibliographyH2: Further readingH2: External links"}␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀