erences\nUse mdy dates from February 2021\nPages using multiple image with auto scaled images\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2025\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from January 2016\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from May 2022\nArticles with unsourced statements from June 2013\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2012\nArticles with excerpts\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from March 2009\nCS1 errors: ISBN date\nArticles with French-language sources (fr)\nCommons link from Wikidata\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNuclear weapon\n133 languages\nAdd topic","chroma:document":"University of New Mexico\n. According to a researcher at the Natural Resources Defense Council, it was one of the most powerful bombs made to date.\n[\n79\n]\nJune 7, 1960: the\n1960 Fort Dix IM-99 accident\ndestroyed a\nBoeing CIM-10 Bomarc\nnuclear missile and shelter and contaminated the\nBOMARC Missile Accident Site\nin New Jersey.\nJanuary 24, 1961: the\n1961 Goldsboro B-52 crash\noccurred near\nGoldsboro, North Carolina\n. A\nBoeing B-52 Stratofortress\ncarrying two\nMark 39 nuclear bombs\nbroke up in mid-air, dropping its nuclear payload in the process. One of the weapons went through every one of its stages of its firing sequence, save one safety switch.\n[\n80\n]\n1965 Philippine Sea A-4 crash\n, where a\nSkyhawk\nattack aircraft with a nuclear weapon fell into the sea.\n[\n81\n]\nThe pilot, the aircraft, and the\nB43 nuclear bomb\nwere never recovered.\n[\n82\n]\nIt was not until 1989 that\nthe Pentagon\nrevealed the loss of the one-megaton bomb.\n[\n83\n]\nJanuary 17, 1966: the\n1966 Palomares B-52 crash","headers":"H2: ContentsH1: Nuclear weaponH2: Testing and deploymentH2: TypesH3: Fission weaponsH3: Fusion weaponsH3: Other typesH4: Tactical nuclear weaponsH2: Weapons deliveryH2: Nuclear strateg