sto\nSmiling Sun\nNuclear technology portal\nCategory\nAuthority control databases\nInternational\nGND\nNational\nUnited States\nFrance\nBnF data\nJapan\nCzech Republic\nSpain\nIsrael\nOther\nHistorical Dictionary of Switzerland\nNARA\nYale LUX\nRetrieved from \"\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nuclear_weapon&oldid=1337841487\n\"\nCategories\n:\nNuclear weapons\nAmerican inventions\nBombs\nNuclear bombs\nWeapons and ammunition introduced in 1945\nHidden categories:\nAll articles with dead external links\nArticles with dead external links from March 2025\nWebarchive template wayback links\nAll accuracy disputes\nArticles with disputed statements from July 2013\nCS1 maint: archived copy as title\nArticles with short description\nShort description is different from Wikidata\nWikipedia pages semi-protected against vandalism\nWikipedia indefinitely move-protected pages\nArticles needing additional references from May 2022\nAll articles needing additional references\nUse mdy dates from February 2021\nPages using multiple image with auto scaled images\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2025\nAll articles containing potentially dated statements\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from January 2016\nAll articles with unsourced statements\nArticles with unsourced statements from May 2022\nArticles with unsourced statements from June 2013\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from 2012\nArticles with excerpts\nArticles containing potentially dated statements from March 2009\nCS1 errors: ISBN date\nArticles with French-language sources (fr)\nCommons link from Wikidata\nArticles containing video clips\nSearch\nSearch\nNuclear weapon\n133 languages\nAdd topic","headers":"H2: ContentsH1: Nuclear weaponH2: Testing and deploymentH2: TypesH3: Fission weaponsH3: Fusion weaponsH3: Other typesH4: Tactical nuclear weaponsH2: Weapons deliveryH2: Nuclear strategyH2: Governance, control, and lawH3: DisarmamentH3: United NationsH2: Launch authorityH2: ControversyH3: EthicsH3: Notable nuclear weapons accidentsH3: Nuclear testing and falloutH2: Effects of nuclear explosionsH3: Effects of nuclear explosions on human healthH3: Effects of nuclear warH3: Public oppositionH2: Costs and technology spin-offsH2: Non-weapons usesH2: History of developmentH2: See alsoH2: NotesH2: ReferencesH3: BibliographyH2: Further readingH2: External links","title":"Nuclear weapon - Wikipedia","source":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon","chroma:document":"B43 nuclear bomb\nwere never recovered.\n[\n82\n]\nIt was not until 1989 that\nthe Pentagon\nrevealed the loss of the one-megaton bomb.\n[\n83\n]\nJanuary 17, 1966: the\n1966 Palomares B-52 crash\noccurred when a\nB-52G bomber\nof the\nUSAF\ncollided with a\nKC-135 tanker\nduring\nmid-air refuelling\noff the coast of\nSpain\n. The KC-135 was completely destroyed when its fuel load ignited, killing all four crew members. The B-52G broke apart, killing three of the seven crew members aboard.\n[\n84\n]\nOf the four\nMk28\ntype\nhydrogen bombs\nthe B-52G carried,\n[\n85\n]\nthree were found on land near\nAlmer√≠a\n, Spain. The non-nuclear explosives in two of the weapons detonated upon impact with the ground, resulting in the contamination of a 2-square-kilometer (490-acre) (0.78 square mile) area by\nradioactive\nplutonium\n. The fourth, which fell into the\nMediterranean Sea\n, was recovered intact after a 2\n1\n‚ĀĄ\n2\n-month-long search.\n[\n86\n]\nJanuary 21, 1968: the\n1968 Thule Air Base B-52 crash\ninvolved a\nUnited States Air Force"}␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀